[1] FAO, OIE, WHO conference -- Rome
Date: Thu, 5 Feb 2004
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Associated Press via NewsComAu, 5 Feb 2004 [edited]
<http://www.news.com.au/common/story_page/0,4057,8588860%255E401,00.html>

Experts call for end to mass slaughter
--------------------------------------
Experts at an urgent meeting on bird flu will urge animal vaccination as an
alternative to slaughtering millions more birds in efforts to contain the
disease, which has claimed 15 [human] lives in Asia.
Officials from the Food and Agriculture Organisation [FAO], the World
Health Organisation [WHO], authorities from affected countries, and other
experts began meeting yesterday to find a unified approach to tackling the
disease.
"People totally agree that we don't need to kill so many chickens or
birds," said Hualan Chen of the Chinese Agriculture Ministry.
Dewan Sibartie of the World Animal Health Organisation [OIE] said the
meetings recommendations included "the option of vaccination."
Health officials have said safely destroying infected birds is the best way
to contain the disease, but mass slaughter and import bans have ravaged
Asia's poultry industry.
Experts also fear that threatened species could come under threat if too
many wild birds are culled. Some 50 million chickens have already been
slaughtered in hopes of containing the disease.
The conference, held at the UN food agency's headquarters in Rome, will
present its findings at a news conference tomorrow. The recommendations
will focus on coordination, surveillance, and transparency in reporting,
the FAO said.
Sibartie said some affected countries had failed to pass on local
information about outbreaks to the OIE within the required time frame of 24
hours. "Had they reported in time, we could have taken more timely action.
We could have provided expertise and other kinds of assistance a long time
back," Sibartie said.
In a conference call with representatives from affected countries,
including China, Thailand, Laos, Cambodia, and Indonesia, experts stressed
that withholding information would let the disease to spread further and
cripple trade.
"I think we made very clear to them the importance of transparent and
timely reporting and I think they have got the message," Sibartie said.
Juan Lubroth, an animal health official at the FAO, said that the
recommendations would include human-protection measures. For example, those
involved in clean-up operations at poultry farms will be made to wear
protective gear and trained on how to use it. "We've also discussed
rehabilitation: how can we get villages and even countries back onto their
feet," Lubroth said.
Measures would include restocking culled animals and re-evaluating
bio-security procedures to encourage good farming practices, he said.
The slowly mounting human death toll has added urgency to the question
about how avian influenza, or bird flu, is spread.
Although 10 countries are battling bird flu, cases in humans have been
reported only in Viet Nam and Thailand. Most of the infections have been
traced to direct contact with sick birds.
[Byline: Aidan Lewis]
[The title of this article might be somewhat misleading; affected farms are
not likely to be vaccinated. Most probably, the experts do not see the
destruction of poultry around the foci as the only way to contain the
outbreak, but include the option of (preventive) vaccination for such
farms/districts as an alternative measure. This policy might be based upon
experience gathered during previous epizootics of highly pathogenic avian
influenza (HPAI), such as the Dutch one in 2003. Final recommendations are
anticipated.
The FAO is to manage Technical Cooperation Projects to assist affected
countries in their endeavors to control the outbreaks and rehabilitate
their poultry industries, while maintaining strong links with OIE and WHO.
- Mod.AS]
