[4] FAO support
Date: Thu, 5 Feb 2004
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org
Source: UN News Centre, 5 Feb 2004 [edited]
<http://www.un.org/apps/news/story.asp?NewsID=9654&Cr=Bird#>

UN food agency gives aid to 4 Asian countries hit by bird flu outbreak
--------------------------------------------------
The United Nations food arm has announced it is giving 4 Asian countries --
Cambodia, Laos, Pakistan, and Viet Nam -- USD 1.6 million to help them
battle the recent outbreak of avian influenza or "bird flu."
The Food and Agriculture Organization (FAO) created the emergency aid
package after a request from the 4 nations to improve their emergency
disease control and surveillance systems.
He Changchui, head of the FAO's Regional Office for Asia and the Pacific,
said yesterday the aid would be sent immediately. "More international
assistance is needed to enable poorer countries to better deal with the
crisis," he said.
At least 13 people have died in Viet Nam and Thailand as a result of
contracting the H5N1 virus strain in the current outbreak. Millions of
domestic birds have died or been slaughtered in the Republic of Korea, Viet
Nam, Japan, Thailand, Cambodia, China, Laos, Pakistan, Taiwan (Province of
China), and Indonesia since December 2003.
The aid package will be used to prepare a zoning plan for culling birds, to
train farmers and government workers on safe disposal and disinfection, to
provide protective gear, equipment and laboratory supplies for making rapid
diagnoses, and to begin national epidemiological studies of the disease.
Meanwhile at FAO headquarters in Rome, health and veterinary experts are
today wrapping up a 2-day meeting on the outbreak organized by the FAO, the
UN World Health Organization (WHO), and the World Animal Health
Organization (OIE).
